
[1]gangway

   GANG'WAY, n. A passage, way or avenue into or out of any inclosed
   place, especially a passage into or out of a ship, or from one part of
   a ship to another; also, a narrow platform of planks laid horizontally
   along the upper part of a ship's side, from the quarter deck to the
   forecastle.

   To bring to the gangway, in the discipline of ships, is to punish a
   seaman by seizing him up and flogging him.
